For thousands of years [[obesity]] was rarely seen.<ref name=Haslam2007>{{cite journal |author=Haslam D |title=Obesity: a medical history |journal=Obes Rev |volume=8 Suppl 1 |issue= |pages=31–6 |year=2007 |month=March |pmid=17316298 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-789X.2007.00314.x |url=}}</ref> It was not until the 20th century that it became common, so much so that in 1997 the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) formally recognized obesity as a global epidemic.<ref name=Caballero>{{cite journal |author=Caballero B |title=The global epidemic of obesity: An overview |journal=Epidemiol Rev |volume=29 |issue= |pages=1–5 |year=2007 |pmid=17569676 |doi=10.1093/epirev/mxm012 |url=}}</ref> As of 2005 the WHO estimates that at least 400 million adults (9.8%) are obese, with higher rates among women than men.<ref name=WHO2000>{{cite book | author=World Health Organization | title=Technical report series 894: Obesity: Preventing and managing the global epidemic. | location=Geneva | publisher=World Health Organization | year=2000 | url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_894_(part1).pdf | format=PDF | isbn=92-4-120894-5}}</ref>  

As of 2008, The World Health Organization claimed that 1.5 billion adults, 20 and older, were overweight and of these over 200 million men and nearly 300 million women were obese.<ref name="Data and statistics">{{cite web|title=Obesity and overweight|work=World Health Organization}}</ref> The rate of obesity also increases with age at least up to 50 or 60&nbsp;years old.<ref name=Kopelman2005>{{cite book|author=Peter G. Kopelman, Ian D. Caterson,  Michael J. Stock,  William H. Dietz|title=Clinical obesity in adults and children: In Adults and Children|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|location= |year=2005|page=493 |isbn=1-4051-1672-2|url=http://books.google.com/?id=u7RvldSr5M0C}}</ref> 

Once considered a problem only of high-income countries, obesity rates are rising worldwide. These increases have been felt most dramatically in urban settings.<ref name=WHO2000/>  The only remaining region of the world where obesity is not common is sub-Saharan Africa.<ref name=HaslamJames>{{cite journal |author=Haslam DW, James WP |title=Obesity |journal=Lancet |volume=366 |issue=9492 |pages=1197–209 |year=2005 |month=October |pmid=16198769 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)67483-1 |url=}}</ref>

==Africa==
{{See also|Obesity in the Middle East and North Africa}}
Obesity rates in Western Africa are estimated to be 10%.  Rates of obesity among women are three times those found in men.  In urban West Africa rates of obesity have more than doubled in the last 15 years.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Abubakari AR, Lauder W, Agyemang C, Jones M, Kirk A, Bhopal RS |title=Prevalence and time trends in obesity among adult West African populations: a meta-analysis |journal=Obes Rev |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=297–311 |year=2008 |month=July |pmid=18179616 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-789X.2007.00462.x |url=}}</ref>

===Egypt===
The peasants in Egypt believe that fatness is proper as the “envelope for conception;” therefore, there is enough room to bear and give warmth to the child.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown & Konner|title=An Anthropological Perspective on Obesity|publisher=Mayfield Publishing Company|isbn=1-55934-723-6}}</ref>

== Asia ==
===China===
{{main|Obesity in China}}
China is currently facing challenges of overnutrition.<ref name=FAOChina/>  This is believed to be primarily due to the rapid declines in physical activity and changing dietary habits which have occurred between the 1980s and the 2000s.  The decline in physical activity is attributed to increasing technology in the workplace and changing leisure activities.<ref name=FAOChina>{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/009/a0442e/a0442e06.htm |title=The double burden of malnutrition Case studies from six developing countries |work=Food and Agricultural Organization of the UN |accessdate=January 11, 2009}}</ref> 

In 1989 65% of Chinese had jobs that required heavy labor.  This decreased to 51% in the year 2000.<ref name=FAOChina/>  Combined with this has been a change to a diet higher in meat and oil,<ref name=FAOChina/> and an increase in overall available calories.<ref name=faoChina2>{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/statistics/compendium_2006/pdf/CPR_ESS_E.pdf |title=www.fao.org |work=Food and Agricultural Organization of the UN |accessdate=}}</ref>  Available calories per person increased from 2330 kcal/day in 1980 to 2940 kcal/day in 2002.<ref name=faoChina2/>  Rates of overweight and obese adults increased 12.9% in 1991 to 27.3% in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |first=Barry |last= Popkin |authorlink=  |coauthors=  |title= The World Is Fat |url= http://www.scientificamerican.com/podcast/episode.cfm?id=8DFF8662-E7F2-99DF-38E67664ABFF1D05 |id= {{ISSN|0036-8733}} |page= 94 |work= Scientific American |accessdate=2008-07-24  |date=August 22, 2007 }}</ref>

Overall rates of obesity are below 5% in China as a whole but are greater than 20% in some cities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/dietphysicalactivity/media/en/gsfs_obesity.pdf |title=www.who.int |format=PDF |work=WHO |accessdate=February 22, 2009}}</ref>

===India===
{{main|Obesity in India}}
[[Obesity]] has reached epidemic proportions in [[India]] in the 21st century, with morbid obesity affecting 5% of the country's population.<ref>{{cite news|title=India facing obesity epidemic: experts|date=2007-10-12|work=[[The Hindu]]|url=http://hindu.com./2007/10/12/stories/2007101260940600.htm}}</ref> Urbanization and modernization has been associated with obesity.<ref name=India2008>{{cite journal |author=Yadav K, Krishnan A |title=Changing patterns of diet, physical activity and obesity among urban, rural and slum populations in north India |journal=Obes Rev |volume=9 |issue=5 |pages=400–8 |year=2008 |month=September |pmid=18627500 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-789X.2008.00505.x |url=}}</ref>  In Northern India obesity was most prevalent in urban populations (male = 5.5%, female = 12.6%), followed by the urban slums (male = 1.9%, female = 7.2%).  Obesity rates were the lowest in rural populations (male = 1.6%, female = 3.8%).<ref name=India2008/>  

Socioeconomic class also had an effect on the rate of obesity.  Women of high socioeconomic class had rates of 10.4% as opposed to 0.9% in women of low socioeconomic class.<ref>{{cite web | author=Praween Kumar Agrawal | date=2002-05-23 | title=Emerging obesity in northern Indian states: A serious threat for health | url=http://www.iussp.org/Bangkok2002/S7Agrawal.pdf | format=PDF | publisher=IUSSP Conference, Bankik, 10 June–12-2002 | accessdate=2008-07-24}}</ref>  With people moving into urban centers and wealth increasing, concerns about an obesity epidemic in India are growing.

===Iran===
In Iran, as of 2008, 6.3% of the population is obese.  Overweight was more among women (39.5%) than men (24.5%).<ref>{{cite journal |author=Rashidy-Pour A, Malek M, Eskandarian R, Ghorbani R |title=Obesity in the Iranian population |journal=Obes Rev |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=2–6 |year=2009 |month=January |pmid=19021868 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-789X.2008.00536.x |url=}}</ref>

===Japan===
Using the WHO criteria Japan has the lowest rate of obesity among the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]] member countries at 3.2%.<ref name="OECD"/><ref>Harden, Blaine, "Japanese Women Buck Obesity Trend", ''[[Washington Post]]'', March 10, 2010.</ref>  However, as Asian populations are particularly susceptible to the health risks of excess [[adipose tissue]] the Japanese have redefined obesity as any BMI greater than 25.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Anuurad E |title=The new BMI criteria for asians by the regional office for the western pacific region of WHO are suitable for screening of overweight to prevent metabolic syndrome in elder Japanese workers |journal=J Occup Health |volume=45 |issue=6 |pages=335–43 |year=2003 |month=November |pmid=14676412 |doi= 10.1539/joh.45.335|url=http://joi.jlc.jst.go.jp/JST.JSTAGE/joh/45.335?from=PubMed |format= |author-separator=, |author2=Shiwaku K |author3=Nogi A |display-authors=3 |last4=Kitajima |first4=Keiko |last5=Enkhmaa |first5=Byambaa |last6=Shimono |first6=Kumiko |last7=Yamane |first7=Yosuke}} {{dead link|date=May 2010}}</ref>  Using this cut off value the prevalence of obesity in Japan would be 20%, a threefold increase from 1962 to 2002.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kanazawa M, Yoshiike N, Osaka T, Numba Y, Zimmet P, Inoue S |title=Criteria and classification of obesity in Japan and Asia-Oceania |journal=Asia Pac J Clin Nutr |volume=11 Suppl 8 |issue= |pages=S732–S737 |year=2002 |month=December |pmid=12534701 |doi= 10.1046/j.1440-6047.11.s8.19.x|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/resolve/openurl?genre=article&sid=nlm:pubmed&issn=0964-7058&date=2002&volume=11&issue=&spage=S732}}</ref>  A 2008 report stated that 28.6% of men and 20.6% of women in Japan were considered to be obese.<ref>Fukue, Natsuko, "[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20100309i1.html TV gets fickle fans flocking to fads to shed fat]", ''[[Japan Times]]'', March 9, 2010, p. 3.</ref>

===Pakistan===
{{main|Obesity in Pakistan}}
Changing lifestyles, owing to urbanisation, as well as diet issues are the main reasons for obesity in Pakistan. According to a recent study, approximately one out of four Pakistani adults (or 22.2% of individuals) are classified as obese.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/world/pakistan/one-in-four-adults-is-overweight-or-clinically-obese-1.271000|title=One in four adults is overweight or clinically obese|work=[[Gulf News]]|date=December 17, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/2007/02/07/worlds-fattest-countries-forbeslife-cx_ls_0208worldfat_2.html|title=World's Fattest Countries|first=Lauren|last=Streib|date=2 August 2007|work=Forbes}}</ref>

===Taiwan===
In 2002, 15% of children range from 6 to 12 years of age were overweight, by gender, 15.5% of male and 14.4% of female were overweight. In the same age range, 12％ of children were obese, by gender, 14.7％ of male and 9.1％ of female were categorized as obese.  In 2005, 14.9% children range from 6 to 12 years of age were overweight, where by gender, 15.85% of male and 14.02% of female were overweight.  10.3% were categorized as obese, where by gender, 10.92% of male and 9.73% were categorized as obese.
<br>
Base on these reports done, the trends were inconclusive, although with more than 10% of the age group being obese, obesity does appear to be a problem.<ref name="Child Obesity">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhp.doh.gov.tw/asp/press/file/200744164312LIAOIB/960404-%E5%81%A5%E5%BA%B7%E5%B1%80-%E5%85%92%E7%AB%A5%E8%82%A5%E8%83%96%E9%99%84%E4%BB%B6.doc|author= Committee for Health and Development Promotion for Children(兒童健康推展委員會)|date=April 04,2007|title=肥胖防治要從小紮根|work=|publisher=Ministry of Health Promotion, Department of Health, Taiwan (R.O.C.)}}</ref>

== Europe ==
[[File:Obesitas in Nederland onder volwassenen (20+) 1981-2006.jpg|thumb|350px|Rates of obesity in the Netherlands between 1981 and 2006.]]
Between the 1970s and the 2000s, rates of obesity in most European countries have increased. During the 1990s and 2000s, the 27 countries making up the EU reported rates of obesity from 10–27% in men and from 10–38% in women.<ref>{{cite book | author=Tim Lobstein, Neville Rigby, Rachel Leach | title=EU platform on diet, physical activity and health: International Obesity Task Force EU Platform Briefing Paper | publisher=International Obesity Task Force | url=http://ec.europa.eu/health/ph_determinants/life_style/nutrition/documents/iotf_en.pdf | format=PDF | date=2005-03-15 | accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref>

Most recent statistics <ref name="epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu">[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/statistics_explained/index.php/Overweight_and_obesity_-_BMI_statistics Eurostat - Statistics Explained: Overweight and obesity - BMI_statistics, see 'Source data for tables, figures and maps']</ref> show that, among the 19 EU Member States for which data are available, the proportion of obese people in the adult population varied in 2008/9 between 8,0% (Romania) and 23,9% (UK) for women and between 7,6% (Romania) and 24,7% (Malta) for men.

===United Kingdom===
{{Main|Obesity in the United Kingdom}}

In the UK the rate of obesity has increased about fourfold over the last 30 years, reaching levels of 22-24% in 2008/9.<ref name=Kopelman2005/><ref name="epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu"/> The United Kingdom now has one of the highest rates of obesity in Europe. 
